[09:57.66]	Me cause to wail but teachest me the way
[10:01.97]	How to lament the cause. I'll beg one boon,
[10:06.37]	And then be gone and trouble you no more.
[10:10.68]	Shall I obtain it?
[10:12.88]HENRY BOLINGBROKE	Name it, fair cousin.
[10:15.27]KING RICHARD II	'Fair cousin'? I am greater than a king:
[10:19.21]	For when I was a king, my flatterers
[10:23.06]	Were then but subjects; being now a subject,
[10:27.56]	I have a king here to my flatterer.
[10:31.32]	Being so great, I have no need to beg.
[10:35.26]HENRY BOLINGBROKE	Yet ask.
[10:36.55]KING RICHARD II	And shall I have?
[10:38.66]HENRY BOLINGBROKE	You shall.
[10:40.13]KING RICHARD II	Then give me leave to go.
[10:42.97]HENRY BOLINGBROKE	Whither?
[10:44.25]KING RICHARD II	Whither you will, so I were from your sights.
[10:48.84]HENRY BOLINGBROKE	Go, some of you convey him to the Tower.
[10:52.97]KING RICHARD II	O, good! convey? conveyers are you all,
[10:56.82]	That rise thus nimbly by a true king's fall.
